1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:12,893
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:14,442 --> 00:00:21,393
I was going to talk about metta tonight, which is just what we've done, this practice of goodwill.

3
00:00:26,141 --> 00:00:30,850
It's something which balances the practice of vipassana.

4
00:00:32,353 --> 00:00:37,040
In vipassana, we're trying to find a very objective position to ourselves.

5
00:00:39,146 --> 00:00:48,079
We're trying to experience what we normally call ourselves as objective experiences.

6
00:00:49,481 --> 00:00:54,728
So when we say the body and we're looking inward, what is it that we're actually experiencing?

7
00:00:55,950 --> 00:00:59,234
When we say an emotion, what do we actually mean by that?

8
00:00:59,494 --> 00:01:05,322
So we take this position of the objective observer, it's sort of one removed.

9
00:01:05,302 --> 00:01:07,367
That isn't the final position.

10
00:01:07,387 --> 00:01:13,599
The final position is even to get rid of the observer so that we're into a pure state of observing.

11
00:01:14,599 --> 00:01:24,037
But the downside of that is the equanimity that we get can so easily turn to indifference.

12
00:01:25,822 --> 00:01:36,322
And somehow we have to re-engage with the psycho-physical organism so that the wisdom that we have can actually be expressed.

13
00:01:37,384 --> 00:01:41,992
And to do that you have to drop the wisdom, as it were, into the heart, the right attitude.

14
00:01:43,727 --> 00:01:50,278
and then the attitude will express itself through the rest of the Eightfold Path in right speech, right action, and right livelihood.

15
00:01:51,340 --> 00:02:01,674
So, whenever you do vipassanā, it really is important to finish with metta, even if it's only a minute, just to bring yourself back into a relationship with the world.

16
00:02:06,942 --> 00:02:11,490
And what we're trying to do is to establish an attitude

17
00:02:11,604 --> 00:02:20,179
So the mistake that is often made is that we're trying to get an emotion going, a loving, sweet, touchy-feely sort of emotion.

18
00:02:21,420 --> 00:02:22,421
And that's a disaster.

19
00:02:22,461 --> 00:02:27,229
You have to pretend that you're feeling loving.

20
00:02:28,211 --> 00:02:29,152
So abandon that.

21
00:02:29,193 --> 00:02:29,854
It's useless.

22
00:02:31,056 --> 00:02:38,828
The idea is that you're training your will, you see, your will to think lovingly.

23
00:02:39,330 --> 00:03:01,794
loving relationship a loving thought you see you've got to be careful with thought but it's an attitude it's a position you're taking of goodwill and of course eventually the heart will respond you do feel lovely don't you when you when you're offering your goodwill to somebody but then the danger is that you start doing this loving business in order to feel good

24
00:03:02,078 --> 00:03:04,043
And that's when it becomes corrupted.

25
00:03:04,805 --> 00:03:06,710
So your attention is always on the other.

26
00:03:08,694 --> 00:03:13,707
Your goodwill is going outwards towards the other as an intention.

27
00:03:14,853 --> 00:03:41,620
you'll notice of course that we turn it also towards ourselves so that's also another mistake that you're very loving to everybody else but you beat yourself up that's not a good thing to do either so you have to offer yourself your goodwill and in so doing what you're creating is a basic relationship to all beings that's what you end up with so you start with the particular

28
00:03:41,870 --> 00:04:05,312
which is easy somebody who's helped you that's easy because of the gratitude that comes up and you go through these stages where you're basically opening out but you're offering the same offerings you see so you're not distinguishing and you're trying to get a universal attitude sometimes the word detached is used but that sort of makes it rather cold

29
00:04:05,292 --> 00:04:16,971
But it's a universal attitude that no matter who or what, it could be an animal, whatever is standing in front of you, whatever is there before you, whether you like them or dislike them is irrelevant.

30
00:04:17,012 --> 00:04:19,857
You still have the same goodwill towards them.

31
00:04:19,877 --> 00:04:21,259
And that's metta.

32
00:04:23,077 --> 00:04:29,555
It's also a platform for which all the other relationships towards people arise too.

33
00:04:29,735 --> 00:04:40,362
Because when you have that basic friendship towards somebody, you can see that if they fall into misfortune or they fall ill, compassion arises naturally.

34
00:04:40,747 --> 00:04:42,228
You don't have to work at it.

35
00:04:42,509 --> 00:04:44,911
You just feel compassionate.

36
00:04:45,052 --> 00:04:46,514
You have an attitude of compassion.

37
00:04:47,254 --> 00:04:54,663
And in the same way, if a person has good fortune, wins the lottery and all that, you naturally feel joyful for them.

38
00:04:56,345 --> 00:05:03,333
And once that basic goodwill is established, these others arise naturally.

39
00:05:03,353 --> 00:05:05,454
You don't have to work at it.

40
00:05:09,805 --> 00:05:18,365
And you'll notice that we have these four basic blessings.

41
00:05:18,425 --> 00:05:19,548
The one, to be safe.

42
00:05:19,668 --> 00:05:23,577
I mean, that's really fundamental, isn't it, to our human life, to actually feel safe.

43
00:05:24,435 --> 00:05:26,017
That's what you want from the government, isn't it?

44
00:05:26,038 --> 00:05:29,584
You want safety from outer attack and safety from economic collapse.

45
00:05:29,603 --> 00:05:31,586
That's your basic ground, isn't it?

46
00:05:31,607 --> 00:05:32,588
You want to feel safe.

47
00:05:33,569 --> 00:05:42,923
So you're offering people safety, but also safety from dangers that arise within ourselves, from our own angers and so on and so forth.

48
00:05:43,925 --> 00:05:45,988
Everybody wants to be well, physically well.

49
00:05:46,009 --> 00:05:46,870
You want to be happy.

50
00:05:47,571 --> 00:05:53,160
And the last one, which I myself have used to be contented and in harmony with the world,

51
00:05:53,545 --> 00:06:02,459
is also translated as well-being, or to have an ease about your living, to be at ease with it.

52
00:06:04,521 --> 00:06:06,124
So those, you see, you offer.

53
00:06:06,384 --> 00:06:09,389
You offer through all these different stages.

54
00:06:10,391 --> 00:06:17,862
And in that way, you build up this universal love, which is not dependent on whether you like somebody or not.

55
00:06:17,882 --> 00:06:19,485
And that's really what metta is.

56
00:06:21,084 --> 00:06:27,990
And just to leave you with a final example of the Buddha's own way of expressing it, he talks about the mother.

57
00:06:28,814 --> 00:06:39,485
So a mother has four children and to one, occasionally, she's a friend, just a friend, talks, you know.

58
00:06:39,505 --> 00:06:46,853
When the child gets sick or when one of the children becomes sick, she tends to that child, so that's the compassion, you see.

59
00:06:46,894 --> 00:06:53,742
When one of the children has great success, you know, and all that, she feels naturally joyful, her child.

60
00:06:53,721 --> 00:06:57,146
And when that child leaves home, there's no clinging on.

61
00:06:57,545 --> 00:06:59,447
There's an ability just to let the child go.

62
00:07:00,088 --> 00:07:15,045
And that's the other attitude of equanimity, which is another topic.

63
00:07:15,065 --> 00:07:17,267
So I hope my words have been of some assistance.

64
00:07:17,307 --> 00:07:21,432
May you be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

